"\nCrantius Colto: This loaf isn't ready for baking, my sweet. It has yet to rise."
"\n"
"\nLifts-Her-Tail: If only we could hurry that along. How would I accomplish such a task?"
"\n"
"\nCrantius Colto: Oh, my foolish little Argonian maid, you must use your hands."
"\n"
"\nLifts-Her-Tail: You wish me to knead the loaf? Here?"
"\n"
"\nCrantius Colto: Of course."
"\n"
"\nLifts-Her-Tail: But what if the mistress catches me? Your loaf was meant to satisfy her appetite."
"\n"
"\nCrantius Colto: Don't fret, my delicate flower. I'll satisfy the mistress' cravings later."
"\n"
"\nLifts-Her-Tail: Very well, but I'm afraid my oven isn't hot enough. It could take hours!"
"\n"
"\nCrantius Colto: Plenty of time, my sweet. Plenty of time."
"\n"
"\n- End of Act VII, Scene II -"
